## Getting started

Today we're going to work through Chapter 3 of R4DS2e. Anytime you read a section, make sure to code along with it.

To start, read Section 3.1 Introduction and follow along, running their code on your computer and thinking about the questions they pose.

- Remember that if they have you use `library(somepackage)` and you haven't yet installed `somepackage`, what do you have to do before the `library` command? Why do you *not* want to include that extra step (the one before `library`) in your .qmd file or script unless it's commented out? 
- One key point from the introduction: `dplyr` functions are always in the format `function(dataset first, maybe other arguments afterward)`, and they return a dataset (their output is the dataset that results from whatever the function did to the one you gave it). As you learn each new dplyr function, think about how this looks for that function. Does it follow this format? What are the other arguments? What does the function do, in other words, what is the difference from the dataset you gave it as an argument and the dataset it returns?
- If you have any questions about this or about the introduction, talk to your classmates, Jess, and DJ.

Recall that Section 1.3 of R4DS2e provided examples of `ggplot` code with and without pipes:

```{r}
#| eval: false

# without pipes: ggplot(penguins, ...) + geom_point()
ggplot(penguins, aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = body_mass_g)) + 
  geom_point()

# with pipes: penguins |> ggplot(, ...) + geom_point()
penguins |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = body_mass_g)) + 
  geom_point()
```



## Functions that operate on rows

Remember: in tidy data (which works best for computers), rows are observations and columns are variables.

We'll work through Section 3.2 now. Anytime you're reading a textbook or a paper, it's a good idea to use the table of contents as a guide. Looking at the table of contents for Section 3.2 on the right-hand side of the page, what are the three functions it mentions?

Start by reading and working through Section 3.2.1. Some notes:

- In general, you use the `filter` function as `filter(dataset, condition to filter on)`, but if you're using the pipe as in `dataset |> filter(...)`, `filter` knows the first argument is whatever is being piped to it, so the code becomes `dataset |> filter(condition to filter on)`. Think of this as "Take the dataset `dataset` and filter it for rows that satisfy the condition `condition to filter on`." 
- Notice that the argument you pass to filter in each of these examples is a logical expression, like `dep_delay > 120`. In fact, `dep_delay > 120` is a vector of trues and falses, true for rows in which the variable (column) `dep_delay` has a value greater than 120, and false otherwise. You can check this by typing in the console `head(flights$dep_delay > 0)` and `head(flights$dep_delay)`; do the true values indeed correspond to rows where the `dep_delay` column is greater than zero? I'm using `head` here so it doesn't try to print out the whole column, which is a lot of number to look at. I'm also writing `flights$dep_delay` instead of just `dep_delay` because outside of dplyr functions like `filter`, we need to tell R where to look for the `dep_delay` column.
- `month %in% c(1, 2)` is true for rows in which the `month` variable is equal to 1 or 2 (corresponding to Jan or Feb), and false otherwise.

Now read and work through Section 3.2.2 and 3.2.3. What is the difference between `flights |> arrange(day, dep_time)` and `flights |> arrange(dep_time, day)`? Try them both and see what's different about the output. Note that it will be easier to scroll through the large datasets you get as results of these code if you assign the outputs as R objects, like in this code here:

```{r}
#| eval: false

day_dep = flights |> arrange(day, dep_time)
dep_day = flights |> arrange(dep_time, day)
# then take a look at day_dep and dep_day by clicking on them in the Environment pane
```

Finally, read and work through Section 3.2.4. At this point, you can either keep going with these notes, or create the Lab 2 document that you'll submit and start working on the exercises in Section 3.2.5.



## Functions that operate on columns

Go ahead and read and work through all of Section 3.3. A few extra notes for you as you do this:

- Section 3.3.1: the `mutate` function can also be used to modify columns that already exist in your dataset. If you run the code `flights |> mutate(gain = dep_delay - arr_delay)`, two different things happen depending on whether `gain` is already a column (variable) in your dataset. If it already exists in your dataset, the code above replaces that column with the result of `dep_delay - arr_delay` (for each row, it computes the difference between the values of these two columns). If `gain` is not already a column in your dataset, the code above will create a new column called `gain` that is equal to `dep_delay - arr_delay`. We'll see later on in the course how you can use the `mutate` function to change some but not all values of a column depending on various conditions.

- Section 3.3.2: to use these helper functions they mention, you put them inside the `select` function. For example, `flights |> select(starts_with("dep"))` will select just the columns of the `flights` dataset that start with "dep". What happens if you instead run the code `flights |> select(starts_with("Dep"))`? Use `?starts_with` to figure out how to change how the `starts_with` function handles case sensitivity, and try that out.






